text:
North Hempstead Plank Road (non-existent in 1929). This road lies between Sixty-third Avenue and 63rd Road) south side, between 98th Street and 99th Street (formerly Marlowe Avenue). There was another house north of the Plank Road east of 99th Streets. These properties belonged to the Hyatt and Garretson families. E.L. Armbruster states this house to be the Baxter house and states that it stood on Old Mill Road (now known as 63rd Road) west of Marlowe Avenue. (now 99th Street). The writer believes this house to be one of the aforementioned.

About 1908

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

63rd Road, south side, just east of 99th Street, showing the old J. Tompkins farmhouse. Tompkins was the owner in 1852; A. Backus in 1860-73; and M. E. Lever in 1891. 63rd Road is the old North Hempstead Plank Road that led from Newtown to Flushing.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

January 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

63rd Road (formerly North Hempstead Plank Road) south side, at about 120 feet east of 99th Street. The house formerly stood on the south side of North Hempstead Plank Road west of 102nd Street. This set of 4 views shows the J. Tompkins farmhouse formerly known as 64 Old Mill Road. J. Tompkins, 1852; A Backus, 1860-1873; M. S. Lever, 1891; Dr. Lever, 1896; and Mrs. Lever in 1909 were owners of this property. The house was demolished in May 1926. Some of the outbuilding were still standing on the north side of 63rd Drive about 120 feet east of 99th Street in 1927. This set shows different angles of the house now going to ruin.
